    "jays": {
      "full_name": "Toronto Blue Jays",
      "league": "MLB",
      "record": "15-17",
      "detail": "3rd in AL East",
      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "Kazuma Okamoto turned Target Field into his personal launch pad last night, smashing two homers that propelled the Blue Jays to a <strong>7-3 thumping of the Twins</strong> - a vital bounce-back after dropping the series opener 1-7. Sitting at 15-17, third in the AL East but six games back of the Yankees, Toronto's clinging to wild-card hopes with a fragile one-game win streak, their offense finally awakening after a sluggish April road skid. Yohendrick Pinango, in just his fifth big-league game, ripped three hits alongside three from Sammy Sosa, while Louis Varland locked down the late innings to seal it - no major injuries reported, just the quiet relief of a lineup clicking when it counts. These Jays aren't contenders yet, but nights like this stoke the fire in a division that chews up the middling. <strong>Today's rubber match at 1:10 PM ET could flip the series - watch if Okamoto chases a hat trick against a Twins staff desperate to avoid the sweep.</strong>",
        "updated": "Updated May 2, 2026"
      },
